    <p>The Lea Valley Walk follows the route along the Lee Navigation towpath, from Waltham Abbey to the Thames at Limehouse Basin. </p>
<h2>Sights</h2>
<ul>
    <li>Waltham Abbey</li>
    <li>King George V Reservoir</li>
    <li>Springfield Park</li>
    <li>Bow Creek Ecology Park</li>
    <li>Canary Wharf</li>
    <li>Old Ford Lock</li>
    <li>Enfield Lock </li>
    <li>Tottenham Marshes</li>
</ul>
<h3>Signage</h3>
<p>Sections 1-4 are well marked by signs featuring a swan symbol. Sections beyond that are not marked but work on those signs are in progress. </p>
<p>Three Mills to Limehouse Basin, are part of <a href="/info-for/boroughs/legible-london">Legible London</a>, but there is very little signage on the Meridian Alternative from Three Mills to East India Dock. </p>
<h2>Route sections</h2>
<p>This 15.6 mile (24.8km) walk is divided into six sections:</p>
<p>Section 1: <a href="/modes/walking/waltham-abbey-to-ponders-end">Waltham Abbey to Ponders End</a></p>
<p>Section 2: <a href="/modes/walking/ponders-end-to-tottenham-hale">Ponders End to Tottenham Hale</a></p>
<p>Section 3: <a href="/modes/walking/tottenham-hale-to-lea-bridge">Tottenham Hale to Lea Bridge</a></p>
<p>Section 4: <a href="/modes/walking/lea-bridge-to-three-mills">Lea Bridge to Three Mills</a></p>
<p>Section 5: <a href="/modes/walking/three-mills-to-limehouse-bas">Three Mills to Limehouse Basin</a></p>
<p>Section 6: <a href="/modes/walking/three-mills-to-east-india-dock">Three Mills to East India Dock</a></p>
